narrator: Magic is not extraordinary.
narrator: Not anymore.
narrator: For as long as anyone can remember, magic has been as ordinary as electricity. As regulated as water. As necessary as air.
narrator: No one agrees on exactly what happened. The official reports are careful. Measured. They use words like "unprecedented anomaly" and "containment failure."
narrator: It powers cities. It moves armies. It settles disputes between nations — and starts them.
narrator: To manage something this powerful, institutions were built.
narrator: Associations. Councils. Regulatory bodies that span borders and answer to no single nation.
narrator: They license witches. They assign missions. They decide who is an asset — and who is a liability.
narrator: For a long time, the system worked.
narrator: More or less.
narrator: Then, ten years ago — something went wrong.
narrator: What everyone agrees on is what came after.
narrator: Not the kind that hide under beds or skulk at the edges of old stories.
narrator: The kind that pour out of a single city like a wound that won't close. Spreading. Multiplying. Reaching every corner of a world that had forgotten what it meant to be afraid of something it couldn't regulate.
narrator: Every nation deployed what they had.
narrator: None of it was enough.
narrator: And then —
narrator: A child walked in.
narrator: No backup. No orders. No plan that anyone has ever been able to confirm.
narrator: Just a witch — and something burning red at her fingertips.
narrator: What happened inside that city, no one fully knows.
narrator: The recordings are incomplete. The witnesses are few. The reports that do exist are careful not to say too much.
narrator: What they do say is this\:
narrator: In the span of a single night —
narrator: — every monster that had spread across the world turned around.
narrator: And went back.
narrator: Back to the city they came from.
narrator: The city has been quiet since.
narrator: Abandoned. Overgrown. Left to whatever lives inside it now.
narrator: The child was never officially named in any public record.
narrator: She was never officially anything, after that night.
narrator: But people talk.
narrator: People always talk.
narrator: They say she never left.
narrator: They say she's still in there — the city that should be empty, that no one goes near, that every map marks with a single red dot and no further explanation.
narrator: They say if you listen, on certain nights, you can hear something from inside the city walls.
narrator: Something that sounds like —
narrator: "BAKYUN!"